In [[astrophysics]] the '''chirp mass''' of a compact binary system determines the [[leading-order]] orbital evolution of the system as a result of energy loss from emitting [[gravitational waves]]. Because the gravitational wave frequency is determined by orbital frequency, the chirp mass also determines the frequency evolution of the gravitational wave signal emitted during a binary's [[Orbital decay|inspiral]] phase. In [[gravitational-wave astronomy|gravitational wave data analysis]] it is easier to measure the chirp mass than the two component masses alone.

==Definition from component masses==

A two-body system with component masses <math>m_1</math> and <math>m_2</math> has a chirp mass of

:<math>\mathcal{M}=\frac{(m_1 m_2)^{3/5}}{(m_1+m_2)^{1/5}}</math><ref name="cf1994">{{cite journal |title=Gravitational waves from merging compact binaries: How accurately can one extract the binary's parameters from the inspiral waveform? |first1=Curt |last1=Cutler |first2=Éanna E. |last2=Flanagan |journal=Physical Review D |volume=49 |issue=6 |pages=2658–2697 |year=1994 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.49.2658 |arxiv=gr-qc/9402014 |bibcode=1994PhRvD..49.2658C}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=L. Blanchet |author2=T. Damour |author3=B. R. Iyer |author4=C. M. Will |author5=A. G. Wiseman |journal=Phys. Rev. Lett.|volume=74|issue=3515|year=1995|title=Gravitational-Radiation Damping of Compact Binary Systems to Second Post-Newtonian order|doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.74.3515|pmid=10058225 |arxiv=gr-qc/9501027|bibcode = 1995PhRvL..74.3515B |pages=3515–3518|url=http://cds.cern.ch/record/275578 |type=Submitted manuscript }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=L. Blanchet |author2=B. R. Iyer |author3=C. M. Will |author4=A. G. Wiseman |journal=Classical and Quantum Gravity|volume=13|issue=575|year=1996|doi=10.1088/0264-9381/13/4/002|arxiv=gr-qc/9602024|title=Gravitational waveforms from inspiralling compact binaries to second-post-Newtonian order|bibcode = 1996CQGra..13..575B |pages=575–584}}</ref>

The chirp mass may also be expressed in terms of other common mass parameters:	

:<math>\mathcal{M} = \mu^{3/5} M^{2/5} </math>	
:<math>\mathcal{M} = \left( \frac{q}{(1+q)^2} \right)^{3/5} M </math>
:<math>\mathcal{M} = \eta^{3/5} M </math>

where <math>M = m_1 + m_2</math> is the total mass of the system, <math>\mu = \frac{m_1 m_2}{m_1 + m_2}</math> is the [[reduced mass]] of the system, <math>q = m_1/m_2</math> is the mass ratio, and <math>\eta = \frac{m_1 m_2}{(m_1 + m_2)^2}</math> is the symmetric mass ratio.

==Orbital evolution==

In [[general relativity]], the phase evolution of a [[Two-body problem in general relativity|binary orbit]] can be computed using a [[post-Newtonian expansion]], a perturbative expansion in powers of the orbital velocity <math>v/c</math>.  The first order gravitational wave frequency, <math>f</math>, evolution is described by the [[differential equation]]

:<math>\frac{\mathrm{d}f}{\mathrm{d}t}=\frac{96}{5}\pi^{8/3}\left(\frac{G\mathcal{M}}{c^{3}}\right)^{5/3}f^{11/3}</math>,<ref name="cf1994"/>

where <math>c</math> and <math>G</math> are the [[speed of light]] and [[gravitational constant|Newton's gravitational constant]], respectively.

If one is able to measure both the frequency <math>f</math> and frequency derivative <math>\dot{f}</math> of a gravitational wave signal, the chirp mass can be determined.<ref name="a+2018">{{cite journal |title=Properties of the Binary Black Hole Merger GW150914 |first1=B. P. |last1=Abbott |collaboration=LIGO Scientific Collaboration and Virgo Collaboration |journal=Physical Review Letters |year=2016 |volume= 116 |issue=24 |pages=241102 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.116.241102 |pmid=27367378 |bibcode=2016PhRvL.116x1102A | arxiv=1602.03840}}</ref><ref name="a+2016">{{cite journal |title=Properties of the binary neutron star merger GW170817 |first1=B. P. |last1=Abbott |collaboration=LIGO Scientific Collaboration and Virgo Collaboration |journal= |year=2018 |volume= |issue= |pages= |doi= |bibcode=2018arXiv180511579T | arxiv=1805.11579}}</ref>{{refn|group=note|1=Rewrite equation ({{EquationRef|1}}) to obtain the frequency evolution of gravitational waves from a coalescing binary:<ref name=cqg>{{cite journal |title=Reconstruction of chirp mass in searches for gravitational wave transients |first1=Vaibhav |last1=Tiwari |first2=Sergei |last2=Klimenko |first3=Valentin |last3=Necula |first4=Guenakh |last4=Mitselmakher |journal=Classical and Quantum Gravity |volume=33 |issue=1 |pages=01LT01 |doi=10.1088/0264-9381/33/1/01LT01 |date=January 2016 |bibcode=2016CQGra..33aLT01T |arxiv=1510.02426 }}</ref> 
:{{NumBlk|:|<math>\dot{f}=\frac{96}{5}\pi^{8/3}\left(\frac{G\mathcal{M}}{c^{3}}\right)^{5/3}f^{11/3}</math>|{{EquationRef|2}}}}
[[Integral|Integrating]] equation ({{EquationRef|2}}) with respect to time gives:{{r|cqg}}
:{{NumBlk|:|<math>\frac{96}{5}\pi^{8/3}\left(\frac{G\mathcal{M}}{c^{3}}\right)^{5/3}t+\frac{3}{8}f^{-8/3}+C=0</math>|{{EquationRef|3}}}}
where C is the constant of integration. Furthermore, on identifying <math>x\equiv t</math> and <math>y \equiv \frac{3}{8}f^{-8/3}</math>, the chirp mass can be calculated from the [[slope]] of the line fitted through the data points (x, y).
}}

:{{NumBlk|:|<math>\mathcal{M}=\frac{c^{3}}{G}\left(\frac{5}{96}\pi^{-8/3}f^{-11/3}\dot{f}\right)^{3/5}</math>|{{EquationRef|1}}}}

To disentangle the individual component masses in the system one must additionally measure higher order terms in the post-Newtonian expansion.<ref name="cf1994"/>

